      "id":"books/2013/oct/16/collaboration-hollywood-hitler-ben-urwand",
      "sectionId":"books",
      "sectionName":"Books",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-16T06:00:04Z",
      "webTitle":"The Collaboration: Hollywood's Pact with Hitler by Ben Urwand – review",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/oct/16/collaboration-hollywood-hitler-ben-urwand",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/2013/oct/16/collaboration-hollywood-hitler-ben-urwand",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"8",
        "trailText":"Film's golden era was tarnished by appeasement, writes <strong>Anthony Quinn</strong>",
        "headline":"The Collaboration: Hollywood's Pact with Hitler by Ben Urwand – review",
        "body":"<p>Nazi Germany loved movies, and their leader was, as in so much else, fanatical about them. In his private cinema at the Reich Chancellery Hitler watched a movie every night, then gave his invited guests the benefit of his opinion on it. He loved <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2009/aug/28/laurel-hardy-slapstick\" title=\"\">Laurel and Hardy</a>, for instance, noting how their comedy <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vvxEytUO1pU\" title=\"\"><em>Block-Heads</em></a> contained \"a lot of very nice ideas and clever jokes\". Yet he regarded movies as something more than entertainment; he saw in their power to seduce and bewitch a&nbsp;vital instrument of persuasion. His propaganda minister, Joseph Goebbels, saw it, too. After watching <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2010/oct/28/it-happened-one-night-film-review\" title=\"\"><em>It Happened One Night</em></a>, he wrote in his diary: \"A funny, lively American film from which we can learn a lot. The Americans are so natural. Far superior to us.\"</p><p>If this eye-opening study of Hollywood and the Nazi elite is to be believed, that superiority was purely a technical one. <em>The Collaboration</em> unfolds a story that rather knocks the shine off the golden age of cinema. Ben Urwand argues that once Hitler ascended to power in 1933 the major Hollywood studios tacitly agreed not to portray Germany in an unfavourable light or to&nbsp;mention its persecution of the Jews. On occasion they went to extraordinary lengths to suppress any mention of the word \"Jew\" at all. Urwand has done some energetic digging in the archives, quoting letters, memos and newspaper reports to uncover a shameful policy of compromise and kowtowing on the part of the studio bosses. And what lends the story its peculiar irony is that those bosses who did their utmost to appease the crazed ideology of Nazism were by and large Jews themselves.</p><p>The story properly begins in December 1930 when the film of Erich Maria Remarque's <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2003/nov/03/1\" title=\"\"><em>All Quiet on the Western Front</em></a> provoked rioting in a Berlin cinema. Remarque's anti-war message and its supposedly unpatriotic picture of German soldiery had outraged the Nazi faithful, who broke up the screening, threw stink bombs and released white mice into the crowd. Six days later the chief censor Ernst Seeger banned the film on&nbsp;the grounds that it harmed the national image. Universal Pictures, which had made the film, agreed to significant cuts in its release elsewhere. Two years later a&nbsp;law was passed regulating worldwide distribution of any film considered anti-German; Hollywood studios saw the writing on the wall – conform, or lose the profits emanating from the German market. Their decision does not seem to have been one they agonised over.</p><p>After 1933 the Nazis' editorial stranglehold was tightened by the appointment of their very own watchdog in Los Angeles. This was a&nbsp;former diplomat, Georg Gyssling. (I&nbsp;winced every time I read that name, tainting by its closeness the innocence of my favourite English novelist.) His job was&nbsp;to vet, and thence to veto, any film coming out of Hollywood that might be detrimental to \"German prestige\". One such was a script written by Herman J Mankiewicz (later to write <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/76006/citizen.kane\" title=\"\"><em>Citizen Kane</em></a>) entitled <em>The Mad Dog of Europe</em>, a story explicitly about the destruction of a Jewish family in Hitler's Germany. Since the film was not attached to any studio, Gyssling applied to the Hays Office, whose Production Code seal was vital to a film's US distribution. Hays's LA censor, a sinister figure named Joseph Breen, composed this memo: \"Because of the large number of Jews active in the motion picture industry in this country, the charge is certain to be made that the Jews, as a class, are behind an anti-Hitler picture and using the entertainment screen for their own personal propaganda purposes. The entire industry, because of this, is likely to be&nbsp;indicted for the action of a&nbsp;mere handful.\" This warning, bizarrely argued, was nevertheless heeded: <em>The&nbsp;Mad Dog of Europe</em> was abandoned, and it marked a turning point in the collaboration. Studios henceforth would avoid Jewish subjects lest they provoked an anti-Jewish reaction in the US. A vested interest could now masquerade as a moral principle.</p><p>Urwand sharpens his indictment with remorseless intent, if not with any detectable sense of humour. The subject is a deeply serious one, of course – an entire industry is in the dock, with good reason – but the po-faced absurdity of the Nazis' ideological rationale would at times make a cat laugh. There is, for instance, something wildly comical in a regime that gives a pass to <em>King Kong</em> but bans <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tarzan_the_Ape_Man_%281932_film%29\" title=\"\"><em>Tarzan the Ape Man</em></a> – \"a film … that tends to imply that a jungle man, virtually an ape, is capable of the noblest impulses of the soul and is a worthy marriage partner, certainly runs against the tendencies of National Socialism with regard to population politics\". And the ironies start to multiply when a film such as <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scarface_%281932_film%29\" title=\"\"><em>Scarface</em></a> was banned as a threat to civil order – a&nbsp;gangster picture outlawed by a&nbsp;gangster state. Urwand, who is a&nbsp;junior fellow at Harvard, remains rather beetle-browed.</p><p>A mixture of German expediency and American pusillanimity maintained the collaboration between 1933 and 1939. The Nazis, unwilling to have themselves cast as villains in the world's most popular form of entertainment, kept a watchful eye on the Hollywood production line. The studios, protective of their business interests, continued to trim their sails accordingly, aware that Gyssling and Breen were lurking in the shadows, ready to be offended. One of the most infamous episodes related here concerns the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/It_Can%27t_Happen_Here\" title=\"\">Sinclair Lewis novel <em>It Can't Happen Here</em></a>, the tale of an ambitious senator who steals the 1936 presidential nomination to become \"the Chief\" – in other words, America's first dictator. MGM purchased the screen rights and hired a talented screenwriter, Sidney Howard, to adapt it. Breen, having read the script, snapped into action, writing a seven-page letter urging Louis B Mayer not to make the film, which he considered \"dangerous\" and&nbsp;\"inflammatory\". Mayer, enthused by the idea of Hollywood's first major anti-fascist picture, decided to push ahead anyway, and might have got his way had not the chair of the film committee of the Central Conference of American Rabbis got wind of the project. The latter wrote to Will Hays: \"The only wise method to pursue in these days of virulent antisemitism is to have no picture in which the Jewish Problem is ventilated.\" Hays got together with Mayer, and some days later MGM dropped <em>It Can't Happen Here</em>, on the grounds of \"casting difficulties\". A disgusted Sinclair Lewis rightly suspected otherwise: \"I&nbsp;wrote <em>It Can't Happen Here</em>, but I&nbsp;begin to think it certainly can.\"</p><p>Balancing this unsavoury roll call of appeasers and colluders, the story has a late-arriving hero: <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ben_Hecht\" title=\"\">Ben Hecht</a>, Jewish screenwriter and activist, courageously strove to publicise the plight of Europe's Jews, helped to create the War Refugee Board, and delivered a savage verdict on his government's failure to intervene: \"The Roosevelt-Churchill attitude towards Jews will go down in history as part of [the Nazis'] extermination plan.\" But that's a different issue. This book's verdict on the studios has already caused conniptions among some US commentators. The&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/culture/2013/09/how-could-harvard-have-published-ben-urwands-the-collaboration.html\" title=\"\">New Yorker film critic David Denby has deplored Urwand's use of the term \"collaboration\"</a> as \"scholarly sensationalism\", and has taken Harvard University Press to task for publishing the book without proper \"fact-checking\". But some basic facts in Urwand's thesis look incontrovertible. The studio bosses could have stood up to the likes of Breen and Gyssling, but they didn't. They could have supported their own film-makers and helped alert movie-goers everywhere to a genocidal crime, but they didn't. They could have been <em>mensches</em>, but they acted like stooges.</p><p>• Anthony Quinn's novels include <em>The Streets</em> and <em>Half of the Human Race</em>.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/419924838|2013-10-17T12:52:58Z|564ee535ea1dfb91fa876e0c72814a2eef0704e1 -->",
