        "newspaperPageNumber":"11",
        "trailText":"By dispensing with the female perspective and concentrating on the inadequate male friendships at the heart of the book, Norman Rush would have created a harsher, but better, novel, says <strong>Rachel Cusk</strong>",
        "headline":"Subtle Bodies by Norman Rush – review",
        "body":"<p><em>Subtle Bodies</em> is the third novel by the American author Norman Rush, whose book <em>Mating</em> won the National Book award in 1991. The story concerns the reunion in middle age of a group of male university friends whose leading light, Douglas, has continued to mesmerise them in adulthood to the extent that they have all failed to grow up. Douglas, however, has died, having accidentally driven his ride-on mower over the edge of a&nbsp;ravine on his vast country estate. The&nbsp;men gather from their separate corners of the Earth at the scene, where, with Douglas's widow and teenage son, they attempt to organise a&nbsp;memorial service and to unravel the enigma of their friend, whose Evelyn Waugh-ish demise has left them with numerous mysteries to solve.</p><p>What proceeds might be described as the wrong kind of masterclass, for <em>Subtle Bodies</em> is a&nbsp;novel whose assumptions are so thoroughly back to front that it offers an oddly lucid account of its own shortcomings. What sets out to be a&nbsp;semi-satirical commentary on the nature of male friendships becomes a&nbsp;lost narrative with nothing at its heart, as though the author had pursued the subject only to discover that it was empty. &quot;There is no permanent friendship between men, among men,&quot; one of the characters observes. &quot;Something goes wrong, somebody marries the wrong person, somebody advances too fast, somebody converts, somebody refuses good advice or bad advice, it&nbsp;didn't matter. It went up in a flash.&quot;</p><p>In trying to capture this impermanence, Rush creates a lot of uphill work for reader and writer alike. <em>Subtle Bodies</em> is like a&nbsp;house that has been built in the&nbsp;wrong place: he has situated his narrative so that it stands counter to the elements, where things are made unnecessarily difficult and nothing he&nbsp;needs is to hand. None of his characters is in their customary physical or emotional environment; the person whose habitat they occupy is no longer there; the source of group connection is out of date and irrelevant; and the relentless approach of the memorial service is both stressful and lacking in any dividend for the reader, who never met Douglas, nor ever will, and has to be reminded at frequent intervals of his importance.</p><p>The narrative allies itself with Ned, a&nbsp;charity worker and&nbsp;political activist, and the member of the&nbsp;group least certain of Douglas's friendship and esteem; and also, increasingly, with Ned's wife Nina, who has pursued Ned&nbsp;all the way to Douglas's estate so that they can make love at the time most propitious to conception. This is&nbsp;an unpromising beginning for any female character, but it is also too obviously an excuse to import someone into the&nbsp;novel who can redress its structural problems.</p><p>As well as exemplifying the nurturing female qualities the boys' club lacks, Nina has to fill in the missing acres of backstory; explain the novel's land<sup></sup>scape, themes and characters; represent a general scepticism in the matter of Douglas and his domination of his friends; and, increasingly, to act as a yardstick of normality while remaining witty, beautiful, clever and&nbsp;kind. The result is&nbsp;that the novel becomes helplessly dependent on her: &quot;There was something she understood,&quot; she ruminates, watching Ned sleep, &quot;which was why Ned had felt so&nbsp;urgently the need to fly east. It had to do with power. It had to do with the old days … his escape to NYU and meeting Douglas and being included in the power group of friends. That had been his great escape, as he saw it … it was like a fable where some grail or amulet has been mislaid and needed to be gotten back by a hero going into a&nbsp;labyrinth or dark gorge the hero had already passed through once … She had a better idea of&nbsp;what he was doing than he did.&quot;</p><p>Rush is so frank in his signalling of his own themes that for a while the novel's lack of emotional maturity and authority – and indeed its dependency – seem to have been designed to echo the stuntedness of its actors, ageing men in the grip of college-era preoccupations. Yet the same frankness makes him incapable of disguising the fact that the novel's game is up: he&nbsp;goes on with it doggedly, dispensing with the more detailed writing of the first half to get the job done. What Rush is committed to here is the idea that men are nothing without women, that their social vision is deluded, their morality without substance, their credulity infinite: it is woman who makes life, order, continuity. Whatever the value of this idea, the novel fails to consummate it: had he dispensed with the commentating, order-making female perspective, and abandoned himself and us entirely to the brusqueness and inadequacy of the male relationships, the result might have been a harsher novel, but a better one.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/419575817|2013-10-17T12:52:58Z|5e90745989bf44d8a63661ebb2827f3c49509fdf -->",
