      "id":"books/2013/oct/16/my-name-is-alastair-campbell-review",
      "sectionId":"books",
      "sectionName":"Books",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-16T08:00:02Z",
      "webTitle":"My Name Is … by Alastair Campbell – review",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/oct/16/my-name-is-alastair-campbell-review",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/2013/oct/16/my-name-is-alastair-campbell-review",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"11",
        "trailText":"The passion behind Alastair Campbell's novel about the dangers of alcoholism is commendable, but the heavy handed execution may make you groan, says <strong>Annabel Pitcher</strong>",
        "headline":"My Name Is … by Alastair Campbell – review",
        "body":"<p>It was an ambitious and worthy idea, to&nbsp;tell the story of Hannah, a teenage alcoholic, from the perspective of the wider circle of characters affected by her drinking. The prospect of using 25 narrative voices would intimidate even&nbsp;the most sophisticated of writers. Not Campbell, though, who gets around it in two ways: by giving similar characters identical idiolects, or, when he's really going for it, dropping in a bit of French for a magistrate married to a man from Brittany. \"You must forgive my lapses into <em>le franglais</em>,\" she tells the reader, about as convincingly as Kishori, a London-born, second-generation Indian, cringingly claims to be \"more British than Her Maj\".</p><p>That there is passion and belief behind this project is obvious, but in some ways that is the problem. Having been affected by the issues of the novel&nbsp;himself, Campbell cares so much about hammering home his point that the reader feels as if they're being bludgeoned repeatedly with the message that alcoholism is a dangerous disease to which all are vulnerable. Indeed, one character explains to her husband, who claims not to understand Hannah's reliance on drinking while knocking back post-work gin and tonics himself, \"It's only a question of scale. You need your little rituals. She needs hers.\" This type of heavy handed exposition occurs repeatedly, with the narrators painstakingly detailing their relationship with the bottle, whether relevant to the story or not. \"As for drink, I am at a total loss to work it all out,\" says Hannah's sister in such an inelegant return to the novel's central theme that I actually groaned out loud.</p><p>Exasperating, too, is the baffling lack of dialogue and live action. Characters give accounts of events as witnesses might in a trial, presenting the reader with their tedious reports rather than allowing us to experience things first-hand. The custody battle between Hannah's parents, for instance, might have been compelling, had we been permitted to sit in court alongside the warring couple. Instead, we are given the key facts by Eric, the pedantic judge overseeing the case: \"[Pat] then went on to seek to refute Mrs Maynard's point that the possibility of future relationships with women meant he would not give his daughters sufficient attention when he saw them.\"</p><p>It's a shame that this energy-sapping technique is used so often, as when the reader is privy to actual dialogue, the novel comes alive – vividly so, in the case of Hannah. When she talks about a day-long bender with a friend's mum, it's utterly convincing, brilliantly capturing the teenager's love-hate relationship with alcohol, from the heady moments of the first drink when \"a bar that felt half empty suddenly feels a lot more than half full\", to the humiliation of wetting the friend's bed. Throughout, it's the teenagers that Campbell does best, another high-point being the narrative of Sammy, Hannah's first boyfriend. Their barbed but flirtatious exchanges give us a glimpse of&nbsp;the type of writer Campbell could be, were he not so bogged down by his mission to educate the world about worthy issues. This may be a commendable life‑aim, but it does not&nbsp;make&nbsp;for a commendable novel.</p><p>• Annabel Pitcher's <em>My Sister Lives on the Mantelpiece </em>is published by Indigo.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/419899197|2013-10-17T12:52:58Z|dac874521bf2e9dc06d47b0e02e45b674d8e2bea -->",
